{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"127c49d5-cefe-44dc-b0a3-cd4786b9ad97","content":"Here's what breaks in each case and how to fix it:\n\n---\n\n### 1. `SpanHelper.cs` — Stricter ref-safety scoping\n\nC# 15 tightens ref-safety analysis. The collection expression `[x * 2]` targeting `Span<int>` implicitly stack-allocates **inside the loop body**. Assigning that narrow-scoped span to `results` (method-scoped) would create a dangling reference once the iteration ends. C# 14's analyzer had a gap here; C# 15 closes it.\n\n**Fix:** Use an array instead of a span for the accumulator:\n\n```csharp\npublic static int[] ProcessItems(int[] source)\n{\n    int[] results = [];\n    foreach (var x in source)\n    {\n        int[] items = [x * 2];\n        results = items;\n    }\n    return results;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `Metadata.cs` — `this` inside `nameof` in attribute arguments\n\nC# 15 rejects `this` inside `nameof()` in attribute arguments. While `nameof` *can* resolve instance member names in attributes (extended `nameof` scope from C# 14), `this` itself is not valid in that context — no instance exists at attribute evaluation time.\n\n**Fix:** Drop the `this.`:\n\n```csharp\n[System.Obsolete(nameof(Endpoint))]\nvoid LegacyConnect() { }\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. `Pipeline.cs` — `with` identifier ambiguity in collection expressions\n\nC# 15 introduces a parsing conflict: inside a collection expression `[…]`, the token `with(` is now parsed as the beginning of a `with` expression (record mutation syntax), **not** a method call. The compiler cannot disambiguate `[with(x, y), z]`.\n\n**Fix:** Use the verbatim identifier prefix `@` to force it to be read as a name:\n\n```csharp\nobject[] items = [@with(x, y), z];\n```\n\nOr rename the method to avoid clashing with the contextual keyword.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a3381780-b430-4932-b66e-b203afeb86e8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about C# 15 / .NET 11 breaking changes. Let me an