f repeatedly creating stack-allocated spans.\n\nFor the second case with `nameof(this.Endpoint)` in an attribute, the issue is that while C# 14 extended `nameof` to resolve instance members, `this` still isn't valid in attribute contexts since attributes need compile-time constants and don't have an instance available. C# 15 probably enforces this more strictly. The solution is to drop the `this.` qualifier and just use `nameof(Endpoint)`.\n\nThe third case involves `with` becoming ambiguous in collection expressions—the compiler might interpret it as the `with` expression keyword rather than a method name. Using a verbatim identifier like `@with` or renaming the method resolves this.\n\nLet me double-check my reasoning on the scoped span issue to make sure I'm giving the right guidance here.\n\nDemonstrating the problematic pattern... I'm realizing the original code is fundamentally flawed—it only preserves the last iteration's result anyway—but the user is asking about the compiler error specifically, not the logic. The real issue is assigning a stack-allocated span to a wider scope, and the fix is to respect those scoping boundaries. Let me think through what realistic breaking changes might come in C# 15, particularly around ref and span safety rules, since the language team has been progressively tightening these constraints. ends. C# 14's analyzer missed this; C# 15 catches it. The fix is to use an array instead of a span for accumulation.\n\nFor the second case in Metadata.cs, C# 15 now disallows `this` inside `nameof()` when used in attribute arguments. Even though `nameof` gained broader scope in C# 14 to resolve instance members in attributes, `this` itself isn't valid there since no instance context exists. The solution is to remove the `this.` qualifier.\n\nWriting attribute fix...","outputTokens":3794,"requestId":"C42B:31EDC7:1D01EDB:20D20B1:6A07C837"},"id":"2413cf5a-3f84-45ff-bebf-b9fab274d53d","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:29:29.566Z","parentId":"26e65c2